<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-forming-quadratic-expressions-by-multiplying-1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Forming Quadratic Expressions by Multiplying 1</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Quadratic Expressions and Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Form quadratic expressions from different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand the structure of a quadratic expression (<m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>), including the quadratic term, linear term, and constant term.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Form quadratic expressions by multiplying monomials and binomials using the distributive property and collecting like terms.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply algebraic manipulation to simplify expressions and form quadratic expressions from different situations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/forming-quadratic-expressions-by-multiplying-1.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/step-by-step-guide_forming-quadratic-expressions-by-multiplying-1.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To activate prior knowledge about algebraic expressions and explore the structure of quadratic expressions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Groups identify quadratic, linear, and constant terms, discuss standard form, and identify coefficients. Groups work with:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Group 1: <m>2x^2 + 5x - 3</m></li>
                        <li>Group 2: <m>3x^2 - 4x + 1</m></li>
                        <li>Group 3: <m>x^2 + 6x + 9</m></li>
                        <li>Group 4: <m>4x^2 - 9</m></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    The teacher circulates among the groups, asking probing questions (e.g., <q>Which term has <m>x^2</m>?</q>, <q>What is the coefficient of <m>x</m>?</q>, <q>What happens if <m>a = 0</m>?</q>). The teacher uses learner discoveries to bridge to formal instruction on quadratic expressions.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <activity xml:id="auto_rdo8tmof">
        <p xml:id="auto_zlsck7vo">
            <em><term>Work in Groups.</term></em>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cbdmbwr5">
            <ul xml:id="auto_6xzu024j">
                <li xml:id="auto_ipan69tt">
                    <p xml:id="auto_fa7f2nfo">
                        Examples of quadratic expressions:
                        <ul xml:id="auto_fk1q43l5">
                            <li xml:id="auto_103qk06p">
                                <p xml:id="auto_3vrhb7jn">
                                    <m>
                                        2x^2 + 5x - 3
                                    </m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>
                                        -4x(x+1)
                                    </m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_0kony30g">
                                <p xml:id="auto_hix46d01">
                                    <m>
                                        3x^2 - 4x + 1
                                    </m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rmmi7q5t">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ggpidwnp">
                        Discuss whether the expression is in standard form and, if not, try to convert it.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9xkxv4o2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_yyk53886">
                        Identify and label the terms of the quadratic expression: 
                        <term>quadratic term</term>, <term>linear term</term>, and <term>constant term</term>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dqem1vkc">
                    <p xml:id="auto_we8vg1bl">
                        Identify the coefficients and constants.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dyk75xtc">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ghttl1ij">
                        Present your findings to the class.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </activity>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            Quadratic expressions are often formed by multiplying two linear expressions.
        </p>

        <p>
            For example:
            <me>
                (x + 2)(x + 3)
            </me>
        </p>

        <p>
            When we multiply each term in the first bracket by each term in the second bracket,
            the result contains a term in <m>x^2</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
            Expanding and simplifying:
            <me>
                (x + 2)(x + 3) = x^2 + 5x + 6
            </me>
        </p>

        <p>
            The result is a quadratic expression in standard form.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    
    <!-- <p xml:id="auto_6nuaprx4">
        By the end of this subsection, we will learn how to form quadratic expressions from different scenarios, simplify them, and use them in various real-life applications. 
        By the end, you should be able to recognize quadratic expressions in different situations and form them based on the given conditions.
    </p> -->
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the definition and structure of quadratic expressions and connect them to the group Learning Experience.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Definition:</alert> A quadratic expression has the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>, where <m>a \neq 0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Parts of a Quadratic Expression:</alert>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Quadratic Term: <m>ax^2</m></li>
                            <li>Linear Term: <m>bx</m></li>
                            <li>Constant Term: <m>c</m></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Types:</alert> A <em>monomial</em> has one term; a <em>binomial</em> has two terms.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Forming Quadratic Expressions:</alert> Multiply a monomial by a binomial using the distributive property: <m>a(b + c) = ab + ac</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert> <q>Remember: When distributing a negative sign, all signs inside the bracket change. For example, <m>-3(a^2 - 1) = -3a^2 + 3</m>, NOT <m>-3a^2 - 3</m>.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p xml:id="auto_l3hm0mlj">
            A quadratic expression is an expression of the form:
            <m>
                ax^2 + bx + c
            </m>
            where:
            <ul xml:id="auto_ufwb6zeh">
                <li xml:id="auto_jye0tp9z">
                    <p xml:id="auto_lveevq5z">
                        <m>a,</m> <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are constants (real numbers). <m>a</m> is the <term>coefficient of the quadratic term</term>, <m>b</m> is the <term>coefficient of the linear term</term>, and <m>c</m> is the <term>constant term</term>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_atwb70c3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_kezfvkw4">
                        <m>x</m> is a variable (what we look for or are finding), and
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lmh0j5ry">
                    <p xml:id="auto_r43mjlgy">
                        <m>a \neq 0</m> because if <m>a = 0</m>, it would not be a quadratic expression.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>     
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pv0eau63">
            In the previous grades you learned about algebraic expressions
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_e8n9ad9n">
            An expression of the form <m> 3x </m> or <m> y^2 </m> is called a <term>monomial expression</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_a1axqgit">
            A <term>monomial expression</term> is an expression with one term.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_csmdse5d">
            A <term>binomial expression</term> is an expression with two terms <em>i.e.</em> <m> a + b </m> or <m> x^2 + y </m>    
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4yl18g15">
            Expressions can be formed in various ways:
            <ul xml:id="auto_vjdw298s">
                <li xml:id="auto_75sj25ri">
                    <p xml:id="auto_4o1kerg7">
                        Multiplying an expression with one term (<em>a monomial</em>) with an expression with two terms (<em>a binomial</em>)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_gej3gk3i">
                    <p xml:id="auto_kgje2qzw">
                        Multiplying two expressions with two terms (<em>two binomials</em>).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <paragraphs xml:id="para-multipling-a-binomial-with-a-Monomial">
        <title>Multiplying a monomial by a binomial.</title>

        <activity xml:id="auto_33ye7v11">
            <p xml:id="auto_61cynls4">
                <em><term>Work in Groups</term></em>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zx15jxek">
                The following data represents the multiplication of a monomial by a binomial. 
                Copy the table and complete it.
            </p>
            <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(x + 4)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3x(x + 4)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3x^2 + 12x</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(y - 5)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2y(y - 5)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-4a</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(a + 7)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-4a(a + 7)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>6b</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(b - 3)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>6b(b - 3)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p xml:id="auto_qxnk2zxb">
                Multiply the monomial by each binomial using the distributive property. 
                For example, for 
                <m>3x(x+4)</m>, distribute <m>3x</m> across the binomial and simplify.
                <ol xml:id="auto_f9xxqj4z">
                    <li xml:id="auto_l296k7fk">
                        <p xml:id="auto_nzqs8vun">
                            What do you notice about the process of multiplying a monomial by a binomial?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_h1yq3goi">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7zfnkcen">
                            How do you apply the distributive property when multiplying terms?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_x8wkcp9g">
                        <p xml:id="auto_fnjckfmf">
                            Can you create your own examples of a monomial multiplied by a binomial and solve them?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_4j8hmpjg">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ddt3krh3">
                            How can you simplify the expressions after distributing the monomial?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_llkb2eoz">
                        <p xml:id="auto_m2gfgj9d">
                            Discuss in your group how the distributive property allows you to break down the multiplication step-by-step.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>
        <insight>
            <p xml:id="auto_8708k2cq">
                When multiplying a monomial by a binomial, you apply the distributive property, 
                multiplying the monomial by each term in the binomial, then combining like terms 
                if necessary.
            </p>
        </insight>
        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
            <p>
                <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To apply the distributive property to form quadratic expressions by multiplying monomials and binomials.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Learning Experience</title>
                    <p>
                        Learners work through a guided example: Simplify <m>2a(a - 1) - 3(a^2 - 1)</m>. The teacher demonstrates step-by-step expansion and collection of like terms.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        The teacher monitors learners as they work, paying particular attention to sign handling when distributing negative terms.
                    </p>
                </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
        </axiom>
        <example xml:id="auto_qqzr9fgq">

            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_89gixuzb">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nxwk4s6y">
                    Simplify:
                    <me>
                        2a(a - 1) -3(a^2 - 1)
                    </me>                
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_974sbddx">
                    Opening the brackets
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2a(a - 1) -3(a^2 - 1) \amp = 2a(a) + 2a(-1) + (-3)(a^2) + (-3)(-1) </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_zlq0q5g5">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp = 2a^2 - 2a -3a^2 + 3 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_kw6tyn09">
                    Collecting like terms we form a quadratic expression:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp -a^2 - 2a + 3 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
        <p xml:id="auto_g1wpic97">
            From the example above you can see that;
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8kmxpt25">
            <m>(2a) \, \text{and} (-3)</m> are the <term>monomial expressions</term> while <m>(a - 1)\, \text{and} (a^2 - 1)</m> are the <term>binomial expression.</term>
        </p>

        <example xml:id="auto_rtq5chk6">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_w0xvwvow">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_kctbezax">
                    Simplify the following expressions to form a quadratic expression.
                    <me>
                        5(2x^2 + 5) + 6x(x -2)
                    </me>                
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_yszeydop">
                    Opening the brackets:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>5(2x^2 + 5) + 6x(x -2) \amp = 10x^2 + 25 + 6x^2 - 12x </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Collecting like terms:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp 6x^2 + 10x^2 - 12x + 25 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Simplifying:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp 16x^2 -12x + 25 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </paragraphs>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Evaluate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding of the lesson objectives.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete the following exit ticket questions:
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li><m>3x(x + 2) - 4(x^2 - 1)</m></li>
                        <li><m>8n(n + 5) - 3(n^2 - 6)</m></li>
                        <li><m>4p(p - 1) - 5(p^2 + 2)</m></li>
                        <li><m>7a(a + 3) - 2(a^2 - 2)</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li><m>-x^2 + 6x + 4</m></li>
                        <li><m>5n^2 + 40n + 18</m></li>
                        <li><m>-p^2 - 4p - 10</m></li>
                        <li><m>5a^2 + 21a + 4</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-monomial-by-binomial">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_g6vln60l">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_fgn82epi">
                    Form a quadratic equation using the following terms:
                    <ol xml:id="auto_pmr187el" marker="(i)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_n7zucxc9">
                            <p xml:id="auto_3qhh7vq2">
                                <m>3x(x + 2) - 4(x^2 - 1)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_x9k5qbst">
                            <p xml:id="auto_o5bk1rog">
                                <m>8n(n + 5) - 3(n^2 - 6)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_spvvskk4">
                            <p xml:id="auto_2025obj0">
                                <m>4p(p - 1) - 5(p^2 + 2)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_spi1gleo">
                            <p xml:id="auto_zf5dlbyq">
                                <m>7a(a + 3) - 2(a^2 - 2)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_atdpjml5">
                    <ol marker="(i)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_vq5pelt7">
                            <p xml:id="auto_557i6ife">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>3x(x + 2) - 4(x^2 - 1) \amp = 3x^2 + 6x - 4x^2 + 4</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = -x^2 + 6x + 4</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_1cik5y9y">
                            <p xml:id="auto_l6au96rg">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>8n(n + 5) - 3(n^2 - 6) \amp = 8n^2 + 40n - 3n^2 + 18</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 5n^2 + 40n + 18</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_mfudx2e5">
                            <p xml:id="auto_lvhqsyt6">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>4p(p - 1) - 5(p^2 + 2) \amp = 4p^2 - 4p - 5p^2 - 10</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = -p^2 - 4p - 10</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ug5e4hj8">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ajb9shpc">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>7a(a + 3) - 2(a^2 - 2) \amp = 7a^2 + 21a - 2a^2 + 4</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 5a^2 + 21a + 4</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_j9iryntt">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_f4rkhr5s">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_ewl7xnx2" marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_hvrz2xla">
                            <p xml:id="auto_e33si397">
                                <m>3m(m - 2) - 6(m^2 + 1)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_spxud8hv">
                            <p xml:id="auto_5g8kkcdg">
                                <m>9x(x + 3) - 4(x^2 - 4)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_87nyrliw">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1ur1xzp6">
                                <m>2y(y - 1) - 3(y^2 + 2)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_v432ls2u">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1csnue6g">
                                <m> 2u^2 - 2(2u + 9)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_m8thbdg3">
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_2kctd2u7">
                            <p xml:id="auto_fvj3pjhq">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>3m(m - 2) - 6(m^2 + 1) \amp = 3m^2 - 6m - 6m^2 - 6</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = -3m^2 - 6m - 6</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_a5fr8kll">
                            <p xml:id="auto_akh1iimu">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>9x(x + 3) - 4(x^2 - 4) \amp = 9x^2 + 27x - 4x^2 + 16</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 5x^2 + 27x + 16</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_87szcauh">
                            <p xml:id="auto_6eic7bxm">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>2y(y - 1) - 3(y^2 + 2) \amp = 2y^2 - 2y - 3y^2 - 6</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = -y^2 - 2y - 6</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_c6wtccgo">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ahfc8f7c">
                                Expanding: <m>2u^2 - 2(2u + 9) = 2u^2 - 4u - 18</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_mnhinhax">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_prbjn2jo">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_305tz3we" marker="(i)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_fp1nkh9c">
                            <p xml:id="auto_7nv6smfg">
                                <m>5a(a - 3) - 2(a^2 + 4)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_tzvincxv">
                            <p xml:id="auto_i3lwlwoy">
                                <m>9x(x -4) -1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2a7pfbij">
                            <p xml:id="auto_dofx3h6d">
                                <m>13-(x+4)^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_qb0cibf3">
                            <p xml:id="auto_yc7selql">
                                <m>p(-2p) + 2(p -1)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_9npy4mkp">
                    <ol marker="(i)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_gz9zm6hm">
                            <p xml:id="auto_6bms77zk">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>5a(a - 3) - 2(a^2 + 4) \amp = 5a^2 - 15a - 2a^2 - 8</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 3a^2 - 15a - 8</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_l0cgcycj">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1dxl7yih">
                                Expanding: <m>9x(x - 4) - 1 = 9x^2 - 36x - 1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_qwr5qe5z">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ylcmi8ce">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>13 - (x + 4)^2 \amp = 13 - (x^2 + 8x + 16)</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = -x^2 - 8x - 3</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5sfjzxh3">
                            <p xml:id="auto_gag9o6kf">
                                Expanding: <m>p(-2p) + 2(p - 1) = -2p^2 + 2p - 2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>

        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_dtlu03mc">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_gund5ura">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_54d7jv83" marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_6ysos0zv">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ihxemqyz">
                                <m>2b(b + 4) - 3(b^2 - 2)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_4lj7vulx">
                            <p xml:id="auto_of4i4rnx">
                                <m>5q(q + 4) - 2(q^2 - 3)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ekgdl1dx">
                            <p xml:id="auto_93pmcs0s">
                                <m>2r(r + 5) - r^2 + 7</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ay1pa349">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ekq6p7g6">
                                <m>2m - 2(m-1)^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_ey3wqszj">
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_xc6yjlhx">
                            <p xml:id="auto_nrudgnjh">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>2b(b + 4) - 3(b^2 - 2) \amp = 2b^2 + 8b - 3b^2 + 6</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = -b^2 + 8b + 6</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_lubm055y">
                            <p xml:id="auto_mcr4x1k5">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>5q(q + 4) - 2(q^2 - 3) \amp = 5q^2 + 20q - 2q^2 + 6</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 3q^2 + 20q + 6</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_fthz2vsf">
                            <p xml:id="auto_klg77qev">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>2r(r + 5) - r^2 + 7 \amp = 2r^2 + 10r - r^2 + 7</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = r^2 + 10r + 7</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_b5xmrfeg">
                            <p xml:id="auto_gu6a130e">
                                Expanding:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>2m - 2(m - 1)^2 \amp = 2m - 2(m^2 - 2m + 1)</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 2m - 2m^2 + 4m - 2</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = -2m^2 + 6m - 2</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide step-by-step templates for expansion. Start with simpler expressions involving only positive terms. Use color coding to track terms during distribution. Pair with a peer for guided support.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Simplify the following: (a) <m>2m - 2(m - 1)^2</m>, (b) <m>(x + 2)(x - 3) + x(x + 1)</m>, (c) Create a real-world problem that leads to a quadratic expression. Solutions: (a) <m>2m - 2(m - 1)^2 = -2m^2 + 6m - 2</m>, (b) <m>(x + 2)(x - 3) + x(x + 1) = 2x^2 - 6</m>.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
